⁵ The conventual buildings at Dorchester have disappeared, with the exception of the foundations of some of the outer buildings and a 17th century school-house, which probably stands on the site and incorporates some of the masonry of a guest—house. They were on the north side of the nave of the chureh, which, with the south aisle added c. 1320. was used by the parishioners. There is no trace in the north wall of the nave of the usual western processional doorway, and the only direct entrance from the cloister at this time was the doorway in the west wall of the north transept, which opened into the church close to the pulpitum.
